scussed, flanked by criticism of Old Left and New Right arguments that is both acute and devastating. In the author's view, the welfare state is best justified as a device for protecting needy--and hence vulnerable--members of society against the risk of exploitation by those possessing discretionary control over resources that they require. Its task is to protect the interests of those not in a position to protect themselves. Communitarian or egalitarian ideals may lead us to move beyond the welfare state as thus conceived and justified. Moving beyond it, however, does not invalidate the arguments for constantly maintaining at least the minimal protections necessary for vulnerable members of society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aSocial justice. 0aWelfare statexMoral and ethical aspects. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aBryan, William Jennings.  aCatholic Benevolent Fund.  aGross National Product (GNF).  aHarrington, Michael.  aHeclo, Hugh.  aJoseph, Sir Keith.  aKeynesianism.  aLaffer curve.  aabsolute needs.  aactivist welfare state.  aadverse selection.  aair pollution.  aapartheid policies.  abias and impartiality.  acapital distribution.  aclientelism in welfare.  acloset altruism.  acollective conscience.  acommercialization and services.  aconditional needs.  acontingent freedom.  aculture of poverty.  adefense contracts.  adisability insurance.  aduty of care concept.  aearnings, and labor supply.  aeconomic justice.  aentailed estates.  aextra-market allocation.  afarm relief.  aflagrant violation concept.  aformal discretion.  afraternal organizations.  agenerosity.  agift relationship: altruism.  ahumanism, and dependency.  aintentional discrimination.  ainvoluntary needs.  alaissez-faire.  aloss from exploitation.  